{"title_page": "Kim Wyant", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Kim Wyant\n| image = \n| fullname = Kimberly Wyant\n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1964|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=5}}\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = 1982\u20131985\n| youthclubs1 = [[UCF Knights women's soccer|UCF Knights]]\n| years1 = 1994\n| clubs1 = [[Orlando Lions]]\n| caps1 = 6\n| years2 = 1995\u20132006\n| clubs2 = [[Long Island Lady Riders]]\n| caps2 = 99\n| nationalyears1= 1985\u20131993\n| nationalteam1= [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1= 16 \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 1995\u20131998\n| managerclubs1  = [[Florida Atlantic University|FAU]] \n| manageryears2  = 2001\u20132006\n| managerclubs2  = [[Long Island Lady Riders|Lady Riders]]\n| manageryears3  = 2012\u2013\n| managerclubs3  = [[N.Y.A.C.]]\n| manageryears4  = 2015\u2013\n| managerclubs4  = [[NYU - Men.]]\n}}\n\n'''Kim Wyant''' (born February 1964) is an American [[soccer]] coach and retired player. She is the head coach of the [[New York University]] men's soccer team, the first and only woman to lead a men's [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) soccer program. She is also the head coach for the New York Athletic Club women's soccer team, leading the team to the 2014 [[United States Adult Soccer Association]] (USASA) Amateur Women's National Championship.\n\nWyant was the [[Goalkeeper#Floorball|goalkeeper]] for the first [[1985 United States women's national soccer team|United States women's national soccer team]], appearing in the inaugural US game in Italy in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |title=Women's Little Trip to Italy Was Start of Something Big |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/43053640.html?dids=43053640:43053640&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+10%2C+1999&author=GRAHAME+L.+JONES&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Women%27s+Little+Trip+to+Italy+Was+Start+of+Something+Big%3B+Soccer%3A+First+U.S.+national+team+was+a+patchwork+bunch+in+1985.&pqatl=google |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 10, 1999 |accessdate=December 21, 2010 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> She played 16 international games for the United States, and was the first goalkeeper for the women's national team and recorded the team's first shutout and win during a match against [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canada]] in July 1986.<ref name=\"hall\">{{cite web|url=http://wleague.uslsoccer.com/home/419565.html |title=Kim Wyant Joins UCF Hall |accessdate=2011-11-30 |date=2010-04-16 |publisher=United Soccer Leagues (USL) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523222629/http://wleague.uslsoccer.com/home/419565.html |archivedate=2012-05-23 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Wyant was the recipient of the \u2018Special Recognition Award\u2019 by the [[National Soccer Hall of Fame]] honoring her contribution to the winning way of the Women\u2019s National Team.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 1982 Wyant appeared in the first NCAA National Soccer Championship representing the [[University of Central Florida]] (UCF) [[UCF Knights women's soccer|Knights women's team]]. Despite her team's loss, she was named the Most Valuable Player of the National Championship tournament. Wyant played soccer for UCF from 1982 to 1985,. She was the team's rookie of the year in her freshman year and MVP in her senior year.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}  In 2010, she was inducted into the UCF Athletic Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"hall\"/>\n\nDuring its first year, the [[United States women's national soccer team]] was a hastily collected roster of unknown players There was little practice time, limited equipment to speak of, and unglamorous travel conditions. The season consisted of a trip to Jesolo, Italy where the team played four games, losing to Denmark, England, and Italy, and managing a draw in their rejoinder with Denmark.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Professional ==\nWyant is the [[Long Island Lady Riders]] all-time leader in minutes played with 8,636 minutes during nine seasons, and second all time in games played with 99.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} As a leader in defense on the team, she helped lead Long Island to the [[United Soccer Leagues]] (USL) [[USL W-League|W-League]] National Championships in [[United Soccer Leagues#W-League seasons 1995.E2.80.932015|1995]] and 1997 and a 2-0 victory over the [[Brazil women's national football team|Brazilian Women's National Team]] in 1999. During her career with the Lady Riders she was the dominant goalkeeper of the W-League, winning Goalkeeper of The Year Honors four consecutive years- 1995, 96, 97, and 98.  She was also honored as the Most Valuable Player for her performance in the 1997 Championship series, and has twice been selected as a W-league All Star.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nShortly after announcing her retirement in August 2003, Wyant was named General Manager of the Lady Riders. Prior to her promotion, Kim implemented the team's very successful camps and youth academy. Under her direction the Lady Riders twice-received the USL W-League \u2018Organization of the Year\u2019 awarded annually to the top USL organization displaying excellence both on and off the field. Kim also served as the team interim coach during the 2002 season, leading the team to an 11-1-1 record. In 2004, Kim was inducted into the [[United Soccer League (1984\u201385)|United Soccer League]]'s Soccer Hall of Fame.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nKim served as the head coach for [[Florida Atlantic University]]'s women's soccer team from 1995 through 1998, and [[Dowling College]] from 2003-2006. She is current the women's assistant coach at New York University (NYU)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Michael Lewis|first1=Special to Newsday|title=Original USWNT goalie coaching NYU men|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/college/kim-wyant-looks-forward-to-challenge-of-coaching-nyu-men-s-soccer-team-1.10812474|accessdate=6 June 2016|work=Newsday|publisher=Newsday|date=September 6, 2015}}</ref> and the head coach of the [[Women's Premier Soccer League|Women's Premier Soccer League (WPSL)]], New York Athletic Club.\n\nIn 1998, she served as a [[FIFA|Federation International Football Association (FIFA)]] Staff Coach in Trinidad, where she instructed national team coaches from the [[CONCACAF|Confederation of North, Central American and Caribbean Association Football (CONCACAF)]] region on the modern demands of goalkeeping. She is the founder of Above All Goalkeeping camps, and is widely regarded as one of the top goalkeeper coaches in the Southeast.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nWyant is a US Soccer\u2013licensed coach and holds a [[National Soccer Coaches Association of America|National Soccer Coaches Association of America (NSCAA)]] Premier Diploma. She has served as a clinician for many soccer organizations, and has published articles in various newsletters and publications.\n\n==BMX career==\nWyant was among the very first female bicycle motocross [[BMX|BMX\u2019er]] in the nation. She is one of the pioneers of BMX riders that started a revolution in bicycling that has culminated into an Olympic Sporting event.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n<!--\n\nShe has 2 daughters Alex and Daniel who both go to the Waldorf school of Garden City.Kim her wife and her daughters all live in Garden City NY\n\nGrowing up in a motorcycle family made it easy for Kim to transition into BMX. On Sundays her family would pack up the family van, hook up the trailer with all the Motocross Bikes and head out to the riding field. One Sunday out at the motocross track she noticed a bunch of kids racing bicycles on a dirt track set up in the corner of the field. She quickly became interested. The next Sunday, in addition to the motorcycles she packed her [[Schwinn Bicycle Company#Child and youth markets|Schwinn Stingray]] in the van. It was the summer of 1974, a ten-year-old girl among all boys, she paid the $2 entry fee, taped a mocked up paper plate number to her handlebars, and lined up across a flat starting line when her heat was called. An organizer pulled the rubber-band across the front handlebars, gave a fair warning, and then, snap, off she flew.//-->\n\n==Honors==\n* 1982 NCAA National Championship MVP<ref name=\"ucfk\">{{cite web|last1=Greenbaum|first1=Jared|title=Hall Of Fame Profile: Kim Wyant|url=http://www.ucfknights.com/genrel/041310aaf.html|website=www.ucfknights.com|publisher=CBS Interactive.|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n* 1986 NSCAA First Team All American\n* 1995 & 97 USL W League National Champion (Long Island Lady Riders)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=NEW TEAM  Rough Riders buy W-League team rights to LI|url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/roughriders2.php?article_id=8435|website=www.bigapplesoccer.com|publisher=Sports Vue Interactive, LLC|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=11 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601170409/http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/roughriders2.php?article_id=8435|archive-date=1 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 1995, 96, 97 & 98 USL W League Goalkeeper of the Year<ref name=\"uaasports\" />\n* 1997 USL W League Championship MVP\n* 1997, 1998 USL W League All Star\n* 1999, 2000 USL Organization of the Year (Long Island Lady Riders)\n* 2004 USL Hall of Fame Class<ref name=\"uaasports\" />\n* 2008 National Soccer Hall of Fame, Special Recognition Award<ref name=\"uaasports\">{{cite web|title=Kim Wyant Named NYU Men's Soccer Head Coach -  UAA|url=http://uaasports.info/sports/msoc/2015-16/releases/wyanthire|website=uaasports.info|publisher=NYU Athletics|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n* 2010 UCF Hall of Fame Women's Soccer <ref>{{cite web|title=Greatness Personified - Pegasus Magazine|url=http://www.ucf.edu/pegasus/greatness-personified/|website=Pegasus Magazine|publisher=University of Central Florida|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five to get inducted into UCF Athletics Hall of Fame|url=http://www.ucfknights.com/genrel/031510aaf.html|website=www.ucfknights.com|publisher=CBS Interactive.|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Long Island Soccer Hall of Fame Class<ref>{{cite web|title=FAME FOR FOUR  LI Soccer Player Hall of Fame to induct Messing, Armas, LeSueur, Wyant in its first class on Saturday|url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/article.php?article_id=33003|website=www.bigapplesoccer.com|publisher=Sports Vue Interactive, LLC|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=March 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also==\n* [[1985 United States women's national soccer team]]\n{{portal bar|Women's association football|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Grainey, Timothy (2012), ''Beyond Bend It Like Beckham: The Global Phenomenon of Women's Soccer'', University of Nebraska Press, {{ISBN|0803240368}}\n* Lisi, Clemente A. (2010), ''The U.S. Women's Soccer Team: An American Success Story'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0810874164}}\n* Nash, Tim (2016), ''It\u2019s Not the Glory: The Remarkable First Thirty Years of US Women\u2019s Soccer', Lulu Press, {{ISBN|1483451526}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gonyuathletics.com/coaches.aspx?rc=1080&path=wsoc NYU coach profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120714222058/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Womens-National-Team/2005/08/U-S-WNT-Flashback-20Th-Anniversary-Of-First-Ever-Match-Kim-Wyant.aspx U.S. WNT Flashback - 20th Anniversary of First-Ever Match: Kim Wyant] (archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wyant, Kim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:American women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:University of Central Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:United States women's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:UCF Knights women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football goalkeepers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Kim Wyant\n| image = \n| fullname = Kimberly Wyant\n| birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1964|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Florida]], [[United States]]\n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=5}}\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = 1982\u20131985\n| youthclubs1 = [[UCF Knights women's soccer|UCF Knights]]\n| years1 = 1994\n| clubs1 = [[Orlando Lions]]\n| caps1 = 6\n| years2 = 1995\u20132006\n| clubs2 = [[Long Island Lady Riders]]\n| caps2 = 99\n| nationalyears1= 1985\u20131993\n| nationalteam1= [[United States women's national soccer team|United States]]\n| nationalcaps1= 16 \n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 1995\u20131998\n| managerclubs1  = [[Florida Atlantic University|FAU]] \n| manageryears2  = 2001\u20132006\n| managerclubs2  = [[Long Island Lady Riders|Lady Riders]]\n| manageryears3  = 2012\u2013\n| managerclubs3  = [[N.Y.A.C.]]\n| manageryears4  = 2015\u2013\n| managerclubs4  = [[NYU - Men.]]\n}}\n\n'''Kim Wyant''' (born February 1964) is an American [[soccer]] coach and retired player. She is the head coach of the [[New York University]] men's soccer team, the first and only woman to lead a men's [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) soccer program. She is also the head coach for the New York Athletic Club women's soccer team, leading the team to the 2014 [[United States Adult Soccer Association]] (USASA) Amateur Women's National Championship.\n\nWyant was the [[Goalkeeper#Floorball|goalkeeper]] for the first [[1985 United States women's national soccer team|United States women's national soccer team]], appearing in the inaugural US game in Italy in 1985.<ref>{{cite news |title=Women's Little Trip to Italy Was Start of Something Big |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/43053640.html?dids=43053640:43053640&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jul+10%2C+1999&author=GRAHAME+L.+JONES&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=Women%27s+Little+Trip+to+Italy+Was+Start+of+Something+Big%3B+Soccer%3A+First+U.S.+national+team+was+a+patchwork+bunch+in+1985.&pqatl=google |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 10, 1999 |accessdate=December 21, 2010 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> She played 16 international games for the United States, and was the first goalkeeper for the women's national team and recorded the team's first shutout and win during a match against [[Canada women's national soccer team|Canada]] in July 1986.<ref name=\"hall\">{{cite web|url=http://wleague.uslsoccer.com/home/419565.html |title=Kim Wyant Joins UCF Hall |accessdate=2011-11-30 |date=2010-04-16 |publisher=United Soccer Leagues (USL) |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523222629/http://wleague.uslsoccer.com/home/419565.html |archivedate=2012-05-23 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Wyant was the recipient of the \u2018Special Recognition Award\u2019 by the [[National Soccer Hall of Fame]] honoring her contribution to the winning way of the Women\u2019s National Team.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Playing career==\nIn 1982 Wyant appeared in the first NCAA National Soccer Championship representing the [[University of Central Florida]] (UCF) [[UCF Knights women's soccer|Knights women's team]]. Despite her team's loss, she was named the Most Valuable Player of the National Championship tournament. Wyant played soccer for UCF from 1982 to 1985,. She was the team's rookie of the year in her freshman year and MVP in her senior year.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}  In 2010, she was inducted into the UCF Athletic Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"hall\"/>\n\nDuring its first year, the [[United States women's national soccer team]] was a hastily collected roster of unknown players There was little practice time, limited equipment to speak of, and unglamorous travel conditions. The season consisted of a trip to Jesolo, Italy where the team played four games, losing to Denmark, England, and Italy, and managing a draw in their rejoinder with Denmark.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==Professional ==\nWyant is the [[Long Island Lady Riders]] all-time leader in minutes played with 8,636 minutes during nine seasons, and second all time in games played with 99.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}} As a leader in defense on the team, she helped lead Long Island to the [[United Soccer Leagues]] (USL) [[USL W-League|W-League]] National Championships in [[United Soccer Leagues#W-League seasons 1995.E2.80.932015|1995]] and 1997 and a 2-0 victory over the [[Brazil women's national football team|Brazilian Women's National Team]] in 1999. During her career with the Lady Riders she was the dominant goalkeeper of the W-League, winning Goalkeeper of The Year Honors four consecutive years- 1995, 96, 97, and 98.  She was also honored as the Most Valuable Player for her performance in the 1997 Championship series, and has twice been selected as a W-league All Star.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nShortly after announcing her retirement in August 2003, Wyant was named General Manager of the Lady Riders. Prior to her promotion, Kim implemented the teams very successful camps and youth academy. Under her direction the Lady Riders twice-received the USL W-League \u2018Organization of the Year\u2019 awarded annually to the top USL organization displaying excellence both on and off the field. Kim also served as the team interim coach during the 2002 season, leading the team to an 11-1-1 record. In 2004, Kim was inducted into the [[United Soccer League (1984\u201385)|United Soccer League]]\u2019s Soccer Hall of Fame.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nKim served as the head coach for [[Florida Atlantic University]]\u2019s women\u2019s soccer team from 1995 through 1998, and [[Dowling College]] from 2003-2006. She is current the women's assistant coach at New York University (NYU)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Michael Lewis|first1=Special to Newsday|title=Original USWNT goalie coaching NYU men|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/college/kim-wyant-looks-forward-to-challenge-of-coaching-nyu-men-s-soccer-team-1.10812474|accessdate=6 June 2016|work=Newsday|publisher=Newsday|date=September 6, 2015}}</ref> and the head coach of the [[Women's Premier Soccer League|Women's Premier Soccer League (WPSL)]], New York Athletic Club.\n\nIn 1998, she served as a [[FIFA|Federation International Football Association (FIFA)]] Staff Coach in Trinidad, where she instructed national team coaches from the [[CONCACAF|Confederation of North, Central American and Caribbean Association Football (CONCACAF)]] region on the modern demands of goalkeeping. She is the founder of Above All Goalkeeping camps, and is widely regarded as one of the top goalkeeper coaches in the Southeast.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nWyant is a US Soccer\u2013licensed coach and holds a [[National Soccer Coaches Association of America|National Soccer Coaches Association of America (NSCAA)]] Premier Diploma. She has served as a clinician for many soccer organizations, and has published articles in various newsletters and publications.\n\n==BMX career==\nWyant was among the very first female bicycle motocross [[BMX|BMX\u2019er]] in the nation. She is one of the pioneers of BMX riders that started a revolution in bicycling that has culminated into an Olympic Sporting event.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n<!--\n\nShe has 2 daughters Alex and Daniel who both go to the Waldorf school of Garden City.Kim her wife and her daughters all live in Garden City NY\n\nGrowing up in a motorcycle family made it easy for Kim to transition into BMX. On Sundays her family would pack up the family van, hook up the trailer with all the Motocross Bikes and head out to the riding field. One Sunday out at the motocross track she noticed a bunch of kids racing bicycles on a dirt track set up in the corner of the field. She quickly became interested. The next Sunday, in addition to the motorcycles she packed her [[Schwinn Bicycle Company#Child and youth markets|Schwinn Stingray]] in the van. It was the summer of 1974, a ten-year-old girl among all boys, she paid the $2 entry fee, taped a mocked up paper plate number to her handlebars, and lined up across a flat starting line when her heat was called. An organizer pulled the rubber-band across the front handlebars, gave a fair warning, and then, snap, off she flew.//-->\n\n==Honors==\n* 1982 NCAA National Championship MVP<ref name=\"ucfk\">{{cite web|last1=Greenbaum|first1=Jared|title=Hall Of Fame Profile: Kim Wyant|url=http://www.ucfknights.com/genrel/041310aaf.html|website=www.ucfknights.com|publisher=CBS Interactive.|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=13 April 2010}}</ref>\n* 1986 NSCAA First Team All American\n* 1995 & 97 USL W League National Champion (Long Island Lady Riders)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Staff|title=NEW TEAM  Rough Riders buy W-League team rights to LI|url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/roughriders2.php?article_id=8435|website=www.bigapplesoccer.com|publisher=Sports Vue Interactive, LLC|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=11 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601170409/http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/teams/roughriders2.php?article_id=8435|archive-date=1 June 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* 1995, 96, 97 & 98 USL W League Goalkeeper of the Year<ref name=\"uaasports\" />\n* 1997 USL W League Championship MVP\n* 1997, 1998 USL W League All Star\n* 1999, 2000 USL Organization of the Year (Long Island Lady Riders)\n* 2004 USL Hall of Fame Class<ref name=\"uaasports\" />\n* 2008 National Soccer Hall of Fame, Special Recognition Award<ref name=\"uaasports\">{{cite web|title=Kim Wyant Named NYU Men's Soccer Head Coach -  UAA|url=http://uaasports.info/sports/msoc/2015-16/releases/wyanthire|website=uaasports.info|publisher=NYU Athletics|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n* 2010 UCF Hall of Fame Women's Soccer <ref>{{cite web|title=Greatness Personified - Pegasus Magazine|url=http://www.ucf.edu/pegasus/greatness-personified/|website=Pegasus Magazine|publisher=University of Central Florida|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Five to get inducted into UCF Athletics Hall of Fame|url=http://www.ucfknights.com/genrel/031510aaf.html|website=www.ucfknights.com|publisher=CBS Interactive.|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref>\n* 2013 Long Island Soccer Hall of Fame Class<ref>{{cite web|title=FAME FOR FOUR  LI Soccer Player Hall of Fame to induct Messing, Armas, LeSueur, Wyant in its first class on Saturday|url=http://www.bigapplesoccer.com/article.php?article_id=33003|website=www.bigapplesoccer.com|publisher=Sports Vue Interactive, LLC|accessdate=6 June 2016|date=March 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also==\n* [[1985 United States women's national soccer team]]\n{{portal bar|Women's association football|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Grainey, Timothy (2012), ''Beyond Bend It Like Beckham: The Global Phenomenon of Women's Soccer'', University of Nebraska Press, {{ISBN|0803240368}}\n* Lisi, Clemente A. (2010), ''The U.S. Women's Soccer Team: An American Success Story'', Scarecrow Press, {{ISBN|0810874164}}\n* Nash, Tim (2016), ''It\u2019s Not the Glory: The Remarkable First Thirty Years of US Women\u2019s Soccer', Lulu Press, {{ISBN|1483451526}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.gonyuathletics.com/coaches.aspx?rc=1080&path=wsoc NYU coach profile]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120714222058/http://www.ussoccer.com/News/Womens-National-Team/2005/08/U-S-WNT-Flashback-20Th-Anniversary-Of-First-Ever-Match-Kim-Wyant.aspx U.S. WNT Flashback - 20th Anniversary of First-Ever Match: Kim Wyant] (archived)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wyant, Kim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American soccer coaches]]\n[[Category:American women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:University of Central Florida alumni]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:United States women's international soccer players]]\n[[Category:UCF Knights women's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Women's association football goalkeepers]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProfessional:Typo fixing, replaced: teams very successful \u2192 team's very successful, ]]\u2019s \u2192 ]]'s (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kim_Wyant"}
