{"title_page": "Jean de Jullienne", "text_new": "{{Expand French|date=July 2018}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}[[File:Fran\u00e7ois_de_Troy_-_Portrait_of_Jean_de_Jullienne_-_WGA23078.jpg|thumb|de Julienne by [[Francois de Troy]].]]\n'''Jean de Jullienne''' (29 November 1686 - 20 March 1766) was a French businessman, arts patron and art collector, most notable as a friend and protector of [[Antoine Watteau]]. He was born and died in Paris.\n\nHe was the nephew of Fran\u00e7ois Jullienne, who retired from business in 1729 and made Jean manager of the tapestry factory Fran\u00e7ois had set up with his brother in law Jean Glucq near the [[Manufacture Royale des Gobelins]].\n==Bibliography==\n* Isabelle Tillerot, ''Jean de Jullienne et les collectionneurs de son temps: un regard singulier sur le tableau'' (Paris: \u00c9ditions de la Maison des sciences d l\u2019homme, 2010).\n*Christoph Martin Vogtherr, ''Jean de Jullienne\u202f: Collector & Connoisseur'' (London: Trustees of the Wallace Collection, 2011).\n*{{cite book|last=Grasselli|first=Margaret Morgan|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Pierre|author2-link=Pierre Rosenberg|last3=Paramantier|first3=Nicole|lastauthoramp=yes|title=Watteau, 1684-1721 ; National Gallery of Art, June 17\u2014September 23, 1984; Galeries Nationales du Grand Palais, Paris, October 23, 1984\u2014January 28, 1985; Schloss Charlottenburg, Berlin, February 22\u2014May 26, 1985|publisher=National Gallery of Art|location=Washington|year=1984|ref={{sfnref|Grasselli et al.|1984}}|via=the National Gallery of Art archive|url=https://archive.org/details/watteau1684172100gras|isbn=0-89468-074-9|oclc=557740787|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Engraving Watteau in the Eighteenth Century: Order and Display in the Recueil Jullienne|last=Tillerot|first=Isabelle|ref=harv|date=2011|work=Getty Research Journal|issue=3|pages=33\u201352|jstor=23005386|issn=19448740|eissn=23291249}}\n{{Jean-Antoine Watteau|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Julienne, Jean de}}\n[[Category:1686 births]]\n[[Category:1766 deaths]]\n[[Category:French patrons of the arts]]\n[[Category:People from Paris]]\n[[Category:French art collectors]]\n[[Category:French businesspeople]]\n\n\n{{France-business-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand French|date=July 2018}}\n{{No footnotes|date=April 2020}}[[File:Fran\u00e7ois_de_Troy_-_Portrait_of_Jean_de_Jullienne_-_WGA23078.jpg|thumb|de Julienne by [[Francois de Troy]].]]\n'''Jean de Julienne''' (29 November 1686 - 20 March 1766) was a French businessman, arts patron and art collector, most notable as a friend and protector of [[Antoine Watteau]]. He was born and died in Paris.\n\nHe was the nephew of Fran\u00e7ois Jullienne, who retired from business in 1729 and made Jean manager of the tapestry factory Fran\u00e7ois had set up with his brother in law Jean Glucq near the [[Manufacture Royale des Gobelins]].\n==Bibliography==\n* Isabelle Tillerot, ''Jean de Jullienne et les collectionneurs de son temps: un regard singulier sur le tableau'' (Paris: \u00c9ditions de la Maison des sciences d l\u2019homme, 2010).\n*Christoph Martin Vogtherr, ''Jean de Jullienne\u202f: Collector & Connoisseur'' (London: Trustees of the Wallace Collection, 2011).\n*{{cite book|last=Grasselli|first=Margaret Morgan|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Pierre|author2-link=Pierre Rosenberg|last3=Paramantier|first3=Nicole|lastauthoramp=yes|title=Watteau, 1684-1721 ; National Gallery of Art, June 17\u2014September 23, 1984; Galeries Nationales du Grand Palais, Paris, October 23, 1984\u2014January 28, 1985; Schloss Charlottenburg, Berlin, February 22\u2014May 26, 1985|publisher=National Gallery of Art|location=Washington|year=1984|ref={{sfnref|Grasselli et al.|1984}}|via=the National Gallery of Art archive|url=https://archive.org/details/watteau1684172100gras|isbn=0-89468-074-9|oclc=557740787|url-access=registration}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Engraving Watteau in the Eighteenth Century: Order and Display in the Recueil Jullienne|last=Tillerot|fi